.TH "nand_subop_get_addr_start_off" 9 "nand_subop_get_addr_start_off" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
nand_subop_get_addr_start_off \- Get the start offset in an address array
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "unsigned int" nand_subop_get_addr_start_off
.BI "(const struct nand_subop *subop "  ","
.BI "unsigned int instr_idx "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "subop" 12
The entire sub-operation
.IP "instr_idx" 12
Index of the instruction inside the sub-operation
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
During driver development, one could be tempted to directly use the
->addr.addrs field of address instructions. This is wrong as address
instructions might be split.

Given an address instruction, returns the offset of the first cycle to issue.
